<div id="review_3787988044" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3787988044" />
    <a title="Mark Davidson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/125607375-mark-davidson"><img alt="Mark Davidson" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3787988044?book_show_action=true">Jan 31, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mark Davidson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mark Davidson" href="/user/show/125607375-mark-davidson">Mark Davidson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780199540112" href="/book/show/5184537-the-republic-and-the-laws">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3787988044" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11666519059621467938">These are two books by Roman philosopher, inter alia, Marcus Tullius Cicero. Both take the form of Socratic dialogues, <br/><br/>In the first, De Republica, a group of learned friends, including Scipio, Cicero&apos;s mouthpiece.  Scipio lays down his principles for the ideal constitution. Incidentally, he thinks the Roman constitution is already the Ideal one. <br/><br/>Much of text is lost, which makes for an interesting reading experience. In spite of that there are a number of interesting ideas, that are, if nothing </span>
  <span id="freeText11666519059621467938" style="display:none">These are two books by Roman philosopher, inter alia, Marcus Tullius Cicero. Both take the form of Socratic dialogues, <br /><br />In the first, De Republica, a group of learned friends, including Scipio, Cicero's mouthpiece.  Scipio lays down his principles for the ideal constitution. Incidentally, he thinks the Roman constitution is already the Ideal one. <br /><br />Much of text is lost, which makes for an interesting reading experience. In spite of that there are a number of interesting ideas, that are, if nothing else, fun to think about.  It's not all wise, some of what Cicero says is quite ridiculous, but I'll not discuss the ideas here in this review. <br /><br />In De Legibus Cicero himself leads the discussion about what the Ideal laws of the ideal state (i.e. The Republic) should be. Only the first half of this book survives, so we only get to hear about religious laws and how magistrates (sort of like British cabinet ministers, heads of department) should be arranged within the country. The most prominent aspect of the laws is Cicero’s natural law, his arguments are not always solid - but they are typically put across nicely. <br /><br />There is a lot to engage with in this text, even though you probably won’t agree with much of it. I wouldn’t consider it a must-read, but I would not discourage anyone from doing so. I would not recommend as your first classic philosophical text, however, as its incomplete nature is likely to make the introduction to that format much harder. </span>
  <a data-text-id="11666519059621467938" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


