          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780199540112" href="/book/show/5184537-the-republic-and-the-laws">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/19936893-richard?shelf=law-politics">law-politics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/19936893-richard?shelf=european-history">european-history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/19936893-richard?shelf=philosophy">philosophy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/19936893-richard?shelf=classical-literature">classical-literature</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer678092017" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4579071603201043484">This is one of those books which I wasn&apos;t sure I wanted to spend money on, but I did anyway, and I&apos;m glad I did.<br/><br/>Cicero&apos;s offers a healthy insight on what he believed a good form of government and healthy body politic.<br/><br/>The three forms of government that are discussed are monarchy, aristocracy, and democracy. Interestingly, but unsurprisingly, Cicero agrees with Scipio that pure democracy is the worst form of government; the best form of government is a mixed form of the three.<br/><br/>Cicero also discusses</span>
  <span id="freeText4579071603201043484" style="display:none">This is one of those books which I wasn't sure I wanted to spend money on, but I did anyway, and I'm glad I did.<br /><br />Cicero's offers a healthy insight on what he believed a good form of government and healthy body politic.<br /><br />The three forms of government that are discussed are monarchy, aristocracy, and democracy. Interestingly, but unsurprisingly, Cicero agrees with Scipio that pure democracy is the worst form of government; the best form of government is a mixed form of the three.<br /><br />Cicero also discusses the importance of having laws that are good for both the government officials elected, as well as the citizens who vote for them. He also brought up the importance of the ideal where statesmen/politicians (synonymous to his time) should be free from bribery, or what we know as special interest groups.<br /><br />His religious views, although he was a pagan, were somewhat interesting in regards to man's relationship to Deity. Cicero actually believed in a pre-mortal existence, which as a Latter-day Saint, I couldn't help but simply eat that up. He relates man's existence to the laws of nature, which was an influential philosophy that would later develop in the Enlightenment Period.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4579071603201043484" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


