<span id="freeTextContainer13237487377780153186">A 3.5<br/><br/>The Republic was better than The Laws. Its a shame that so little of these works survive. What other wisdom could they contain? The Republic&apos;s many missing pieces break it up the read and made it hard to get into the flow. <br/>I was surprised by the science of eclipses. I knew the ancients were aware the earth went around the sun, but the discussion of the various historical figures talking knowingly about what causes eclipses is eye-opening. <br/><br/>The paragraph that spans sections 51-52 in The Repub</span>
  <span id="freeText13237487377780153186" style="display:none">A 3.5<br /><br />The Republic was better than The Laws. Its a shame that so little of these works survive. What other wisdom could they contain? The Republic's many missing pieces break it up the read and made it hard to get into the flow. <br />I was surprised by the science of eclipses. I knew the ancients were aware the earth went around the sun, but the discussion of the various historical figures talking knowingly about what causes eclipses is eye-opening. <br /><br />The paragraph that spans sections 51-52 in The Republic is incredible. These two sentences in particular:<br />"Money, name and property, if divorced from good sense and skill in living ones own life and directing the lives of others, lapse into total degradation and supercilious insolence. And indeed, there is no more degenerate kind of state than that in which the richest are supposed to be the best." Go Cicero Go! </span>
